# Define the query
my_query = """
WITH OrderCountByCategory AS (
    SELECT 
        p.Category,
        c.Gender,
        DATEPART(YEAR, GETDATE()) - DATEPART(YEAR, c.Birthday) AS Age,
        c.City,
        c.State_Code,
        c.Country,
        COUNT(*) AS OrderCount
    FROM dbo.proj_products p
    JOIN dbo.proj_sales o ON p.ProductKey = o.ProductKey
    JOIN dbo.proj_customers c ON o.CustomerKey = c.CustomerKey
    GROUP BY 
        p.Category, 
        c.Gender, 
        DATEPART(YEAR, GETDATE()) - DATEPART(YEAR, c.Birthday),
        c.City,
        c.State_Code,
        c.Country
),
TopCategories AS (
    SELECT TOP 10
        Category,
        SUM(OrderCount) AS TotalOrders
    FROM OrderCountByCategory
    GROUP BY Category
    ORDER BY TotalOrders DESC
)
SELECT 
    tc.Category,
    oc.Gender,
    oc.Age,
    oc.City,
    oc.State_Code,
    oc.Country,
    SUM(oc.OrderCount) AS TotalOrdersInCategory
FROM TopCategories tc
JOIN OrderCountByCategory oc ON tc.Category = oc.Category
GROUP BY 
    tc.Category, 
    oc.Gender, 
    oc.Age, 
    oc.City, 
    oc.State_Code, 
    oc.Country
ORDER BY 
    tc.Category, 
    TotalOrdersInCategory DESC;
    """



# Execute the query and load the data into a pandas DataFrame

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

import pyodbc
import os

# Define your connection details
username = "dariusdickerson79"
password = "CCny24384979"
server = "johndroescher.com"
default_db = 'Fall_2024'

# Define the connection string for SQLAlchemy
connection_string = (
    f"mssql+pyodbc://{username}:{password}@{server}/{default_db}"
    "?driver=ODBC+Driver+17+for+SQL+Server"
)

# Create an SQLAlchemy engine
engine = create_engine(connection_string)

# Define the query
my_query = """WITH ProductOrderCount AS (
    SELECT 
        p.Category,
        p.Product_Name,
        p.ProductKey,
        COUNT(*) AS OrderCount
    FROM dbo.proj_products p
    JOIN dbo.proj_sales o ON p.ProductKey = o.ProductKey
    GROUP BY p.Category, p.Product_Name, p.ProductKey
),
MostPopularItems AS (
    SELECT 
        Category,
        Product_Name,
        ProductKey,
        OrderCount
    FROM (
        SELECT 
            Category,
            Product_Name,
            ProductKey,
            OrderCount,
            ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY Category ORDER BY OrderCount DESC) AS rn
        FROM ProductOrderCount
    ) AS ranked
    WHERE rn = 1
)
SELECT 
    mpi.Category,
    mpi.Product_Name AS Most_Popular_Item,
    c.Name AS Customer_Name,
    c.Gender,
    DATEPART(YEAR, GETDATE()) - DATEPART(YEAR, c.Birthday) AS Age,
    c.City,
    c.State,
    c.Country
FROM MostPopularItems mpi
JOIN dbo.proj_sales o ON mpi.ProductKey = o.ProductKey
JOIN dbo.proj_customers c ON o.CustomerKey = c.CustomerKey
ORDER BY mpi.Category, c.City;
"""
df = pd.read_sql(my_query, engine)

sns.set(style="whitegrid")

# 1. Visualize Most Popular Items Per Category
popular_items = df.groupby("Category")["Most_Popular_Item"].first().reset_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.barplot(x="Category", y="Most_Popular_Item", data=popular_items, ci=None, palette="viridis")
plt.title("Most Popular Item Sold in Each Category", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("Category", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Item Name", fontsize=14)
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha="right")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# 2. Gender Distribution of Customers
gender_data = df.groupby(["Category", "Gender"]).size().reset_index(name="Count")

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.barplot(x="Category", y="Count", hue="Gender", data=gender_data, palette="coolwarm")
plt.title("Gender Distribution for Most Popular Items by Category", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("Category", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Number of Customers", fontsize=14)
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha="right")
plt.legend(title="Gender")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# 3. Top 20 Cities by Total Orders
top_cities = df["City"].value_counts().head(20).reset_index()
top_cities.columns = ["City", "Total_Orders"]

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.barplot(y="City", x="Total_Orders", data=top_cities, palette="magma")
plt.title("Top 20 Cities by Total Orders for Most Popular Items", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("Total Orders", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("City", fontsize=14)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# 4. Age Distribution of Customers
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.boxplot(x="Category", y="Age", data=df, palette="Set2")
plt.title("Age Distribution of Customers by Category", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("Category", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Age", fontsize=14)
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha="right")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

import pyodbc
import os

df = pd.read_sql(my_query, engine)

category_totals = df.groupby("Category")["TotalOrdersInCategory"].sum().reset_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.barplot(data=category_totals, x="Category", y="TotalOrdersInCategory", palette="viridis")
plt.title("Total Orders Per Category", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("Category", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Total Orders", fontsize=14)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Gender Distribution by Category
gender_dist = df.groupby(["Category", "Gender"])["TotalOrdersInCategory"].sum().unstack().fillna(0)

gender_dist.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(12, 6), colormap="coolwarm")
plt.title("Gender Distribution by Category", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("Category", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Total Orders", fontsize=14)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.legend(title="Gender")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Heatmap for City vs Total Orders
# Filter Top 20 Cities with Most Orders
top_cities = df.groupby("City")["TotalOrdersInCategory"].sum().sort_values(ascending=False).head(20).index
filtered_data = df[df["City"].isin(top_cities)]

# Create Pivot Table for Heatmap
city_category_pivot = filtered_data.pivot_table(
    values="TotalOrdersInCategory",
    index="City",
    columns="Category",
    aggfunc="sum",
    fill_value=0
)

# Sort Cities by Total Orders
city_category_pivot = city_category_pivot.loc[city_category_pivot.sum(axis=1).sort_values(ascending=False).index]

# Plot Heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))  # Increased figure size
sns.heatmap(
    city_category_pivot, 
    cmap="YlGnBu", 
    linewidths=0.5, 
    annot=True, 
    fmt=".0f", 
    cbar_kws={'label': 'Order Count'}
)
plt.title("Top 20 Cities: Orders by Category", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("Category", fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel("City", fontsize=12)
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha="right")  # Rotate category names
plt.yticks(rotation=0)  # Keep city names horizontal
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()


# Age Distribution Across Categories
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.boxplot(data=df, x="Category", y="Age", palette="Set2")
plt.title("Age Distribution Across Top Categories", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("Category", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Age", fontsize=14)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

)

# Create an SQLAlchemy engine
engine = create_engine(connection_string)


# Define the query
my_query = """
WITH StateOrderRank AS (
    SELECT 
        c.state,
        p.Product_Name,
        SUM(s.quantity) AS total_quantity_ordered,
        ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY c.state ORDER BY SUM(s.quantity) DESC) AS rank
    FROM dbo.proj_customers c
    JOIN dbo.proj_sales s ON c.customerkey = s.customerkey
    JOIN dbo.proj_products p ON s.productkey = p.productkey
    WHERE c.country = 'United States'
    GROUP BY c.state, p.Product_Name
)
SELECT 
    state,
    Product_Name AS most_popular_product,
    total_quantity_ordered
FROM StateOrderRank
WHERE rank = 1
ORDER BY total_quantity_ordered DESC;
    """

data = pd.read_sql(my_query, engine)

# Print the first rows and column names to debug
print(data.head())
print(data.columns)
# Execute the query and load the data into a pandas DataFrame
data = data.sort_values(by='total_quantity_ordered', ascending=False).head(20)

# Visualization
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
sns.barplot(
    data=data,  # Use the correct DataFrame name
    x='total_quantity_ordered', 
    y='state', 
    hue='most_popular_product', 
    dodge=False, 
    palette='viridis'
)

# Add chart titles and labels
plt.title('Top 20 States and Their Most Popular Ordered Products', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Total Quantity Ordered', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('State', fontsize=14)

# Adjust legend for readability
plt.legend(title='Most Popular Product', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')

# Show the plot
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Define the connection string for SQLAlchemy
connection_string = (
    f"mssql+pyodbc://{username}:{password}@{server}/{default_db}"
    "?driver=ODBC+Driver+17+for+SQL+Server"
)

# Create an SQLAlchemy engine
engine = create_engine(connection_string)


# Define the query
my_query = """
SELECT
    CASE
        WHEN DATEDIFF(YEAR, c.birthday, GETDATE()) < 40 THEN 'Younger Males'
        ELSE 'Older Males'
    END AS age_group,
    COUNT(s.order_number) AS total_orders
FROM dbo.proj_customers c
JOIN dbo.proj_sales s ON c.customerkey = s.customerkey
WHERE c.gender = 'Male'
GROUP BY
    CASE
        WHEN DATEDIFF(YEAR, c.birthday, GETDATE()) < 40 THEN 'Younger Males'
        ELSE 'Older Males'
    END;
    """

try:
    df = pd.read_sql(engine)
    print("Data fetched successfully!")
    print(df.head())  # Check the data structure
except Exception as e:
    print("Error fetching data:", e)
    exit()

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))  # Adjust figure size
sns.barplot(
    data=df, 
    x="age_group", 
    y="total_orders", 
    palette="viridis"
)

# Add titles and labels
plt.title("Total Orders by Age Group (Younger vs Older Males)", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("Age Group", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Total Orders", fontsize=14)

# Show exact values on top of the bars
for index, row in enumerate(df.itertuples()):

# Display the plot
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
# Calculate total production cost
high_cost_threshold = df['Unit_Cost_USD'].quantile(0.75)  # Top 25% by unit cost
low_quantity_threshold = df['Quantity'].quantile(0.25)    # Bottom 25% by quantity

filtered_df = df[(df['Unit_Cost_USD'] >= high_cost_threshold) & 
                 (df['Quantity'] <= low_quantity_threshold)]

# If more than 10 rows remain, sample for readability
filtered_df = filtered_df.sample(n=min(10, len(filtered_df)), random_state=42)

# Visualization
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(data=filtered_df, x='Unit_Cost_USD', y='Quantity', hue='Product_Name', size='Quantity', sizes=(50, 300))

# Add labels and title
plt.title("High Unit Cost and Low Quantity Ordered", fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel("Unit Cost (USD)", fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel("Quantity Ordered", fontsize=12)
plt.legend(title="Products", bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.tight_layout()

# Show the plot
plt.show()
